</div>  </div>
  <div>
    <div id="comment-wrapper-861311"><a id="comment-861311"></a>
<article class="comment clearfix">

	<div class="comment-content separator-solid-grayoffwhite ">

		<header class="comment-header bg-beige-alt clearfix">
			  <div class="user-picture">
    <img src="http://www.bbcgoodfood.com/sites/default/files/styles/avatar/public/default-avatar.jpg?itok=EYlJH5Kp" width="40" height="40" alt="JanBeal&#039;s picture" title="JanBeal&#039;s picture" />  </div>
 <span class="comment-metadata"><span class="username">JanBeal</span><span class="comment-date text-style-alt">21st Jun, 2015</span></span>
		</header>

		<div class="comment-body">
      			<blockquote>
				<div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Brilliant! Very sweet, so you don't need much. As it's so sweet, I would suggest adding many more elderflower heads for more elderflower taste. That way, you can use less cordial but still have plenty of flavour. I wasn't able to remove all the little bugs before adding the flowers to the syrup, so there were a few aphids left in the teatowel. Didn't seem to matter! Was only able to make 3 litres of cordial with the amounts in the recipe.</p>
</div></div></div>							</blockquote>
		</div>

